1
00:00:05,000 --> 00:00:08,750
In episode one we got a quick tour of CueDeck.

2
00:00:09,050 --> 00:00:11,050
Now let's actually build something.

3
00:00:11,350 --> 00:00:15,100
In the next few minutes I'm going to create a

4
00:00:15,400 --> 00:00:17,650
full conference event, add sessions, and

5
00:00:17,950 --> 00:00:20,200
have it ready to run live.

6
00:00:20,500 --> 00:00:22,750
This is 'Tech Summit 2026' —

7
00:00:23,050 --> 00:00:25,300
a single-day tech conference in London.

8
00:00:25,600 --> 00:00:27,600
Let's go.

9
00:00:27,900 --> 00:00:29,900
You land here.

10
00:00:30,200 --> 00:00:33,200
Enter your email and password, hit sign in.

11
00:00:33,500 --> 00:00:36,500
CueDeck uses Supabase Auth under the hood —

12
00:00:36,800 --> 00:00:40,550
your credentials are secure and the session persists across tabs.

13
00:00:40,850 --> 00:00:42,850
First time here?

14
00:00:43,150 --> 00:00:46,900
Click 'Create Account', enter the invite code your director gave

15
00:00:47,200 --> 00:00:49,450
you, or start a free trial.

16
00:00:49,750 --> 00:00:52,750
We'll cover the invite flow in episode seven.

17
00:00:53,050 --> 00:00:56,800
For a brand new account, the setup wizard kicks in.

18
00:00:57,100 --> 00:00:59,350
Four steps — create your event,

19
00:00:59,650 --> 00:01:01,900
add a session, invite your team,

20
00:01:02,200 --> 00:01:04,200
set up a display.

21
00:01:04,500 --> 00:01:06,500
Let's follow it.

22
00:01:06,800 --> 00:01:08,800
Step one: create the event.

23
00:01:09,100 --> 00:01:11,100
Name: Tech Summit 2026.

24
00:01:11,400 --> 00:01:13,400
Date: April 15th.

25
00:01:13,700 --> 00:01:15,700
Timezone: Europe London.

26
00:01:15,1000 --> 00:01:17,1000
Event runs 9am to 6pm.

27
00:01:18,300 --> 00:01:20,300
Venue: Grand Convention Centre London.

28
00:01:20,600 --> 00:01:22,600
Hit Save.

29
00:01:22,900 --> 00:01:25,900
Now we have an event with no sessions.

30
00:01:26,200 --> 00:01:28,200
Let's add them.

31
00:01:28,500 --> 00:01:30,500
Click the plus button.

32
00:01:30,800 --> 00:01:33,800
Each session has a title, a type —

33
00:01:34,100 --> 00:01:36,350
keynote, panel, workshop, break, sponsor —

34
00:01:36,650 --> 00:01:39,275
a room name, a speaker, their company,

35
00:01:39,575 --> 00:01:41,825
planned start and end times, and

36
00:01:42,125 --> 00:01:45,125
a sort order to control the running order.

37
00:01:45,425 --> 00:01:49,175
I'll also tick 'Recording' and 'Streaming' for the keynote —

38
00:01:49,475 --> 00:01:53,225
these flags appear on every role's view so the AV

39
00:01:53,525 --> 00:01:55,525
team knows what to prep.

40
00:01:55,825 --> 00:01:57,825
Save.

41
00:01:58,125 --> 00:02:00,375
There it is — first session,

42
00:02:00,675 --> 00:02:02,925
status PLANNED, showing in the list.

43
00:02:03,225 --> 00:02:05,475
I'll add a few more —

44
00:02:05,775 --> 00:02:08,025
a panel and a lunch break.

45
00:02:08,325 --> 00:02:12,075
Notice the lunch break is type 'break' so it renders

46
00:02:12,375 --> 00:02:15,375
with a different visual treatment in the list.

47
00:02:15,675 --> 00:02:19,050
In a real event you'd add all ten or

48
00:02:19,350 --> 00:02:21,350
twenty sessions up front.

49
00:02:21,650 --> 00:02:25,400
You can also duplicate sessions from a previous event —

50
00:02:25,700 --> 00:02:29,075
there's a seed-from option in the event modal that

51
00:02:29,375 --> 00:02:31,375
copies the full schedule.

52
00:02:31,675 --> 00:02:33,675
Need to reorder?

53
00:02:33,975 --> 00:02:36,975
Click the up/down arrows on any session card,

54
00:02:37,275 --> 00:02:39,275
or edit the sort_order directly.

55
00:02:39,575 --> 00:02:41,575
The list re-sorts instantly.

56
00:02:41,875 --> 00:02:45,625
To edit a session — click anywhere on the card.

57
00:02:45,925 --> 00:02:47,925
The modal comes back pre-filled.

58
00:02:48,225 --> 00:02:51,975
Change the speaker, adjust the time, tick or untick flags.

59
00:02:52,275 --> 00:02:54,275
Save.

60
00:02:54,575 --> 00:02:56,825
Once you have a full programme,

61
00:02:57,125 --> 00:02:59,375
the filter bar keeps you sane.

62
00:02:59,675 --> 00:03:03,050
Type a speaker name — matching sessions surface immediately.

63
00:03:03,350 --> 00:03:07,100
Click a room chip to see just that room's schedule.

64
00:03:07,400 --> 00:03:10,775
Filter by status to find everything that's still PLANNED.

65
00:03:11,075 --> 00:03:15,575
These filters are local — they don't affect what anyone else sees.

66
00:03:15,875 --> 00:03:19,250
That's it — event created, sessions in, programme structured.

67
00:03:19,550 --> 00:03:23,300
In the next episode we'll go live for the first

68
00:03:23,600 --> 00:03:27,350
time and walk through the full session state machine —

69
00:03:27,650 --> 00:03:29,650
READY, CALLING, LIVE, HOLD, ENDED.

70
00:03:29,950 --> 00:03:32,200
Subscribe so you don't miss it.

71
00:03:32,500 --> 00:03:34,500
See you in episode three.
